      <bioghist id="aspace_b4eb6d51a83ebbeeb5288d4cd4178626">
         <head>Nathan Judson</head>
         <p>Nathan Judson was a real estate dealer in Lansing, Michigan. Together with his brother James B. Judson, he ran the firms Judson, Wiley &amp; Judson, and Judson Brothers. In addition to buying and selling Michigan real estate, he invested in gold mines, including the Buck Eye Mining Company in Basin, Montana. After the death of James, he supported the education of his three nephews Wilber, Lowell, and Paul Judson. Wilber travelled extensively in the Western United States and in Mexico to investigate mining prospects on behalf of his uncle. Wilber worked at several mines, including the Buck Eye Mine in Basin, Montana (1902-1903), an unidentified mine in Panama (1905), and the Sierra Mining Company in Ocampo, Chihuahua, Mexico (1911). Paul and Lowell founded the Judson Brothers fruit growing business in Kinderhook, New York.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_c848019f3d419b8a4533661d20f33870">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The papers document the business and personal life of Nathan Judson, his brother James B. Judson, and his nephews Wilber, Lowell, and Paul. Correspondence and financial records document the activity of the firms Judson, Wiley &amp; Judson and Judson Brothers, in late nineteenth-century and early twentieth-century Michigan. Correspondence documents the buying and selling of Michigan real estate, mining investments in various western states and Mexico (including the Buck Eye Mining Company in Basin, Montana and the Sierra Mining Company in Ocampo, Chihuahua, Mexico), and the horticulture business in the Hudson Valley of New York State in the 1910s and 1920s. Other than correspondence, the collection includes fragmentary financial records (including bank records and cancelled cheques) and real estate documents (including deeds and abstracts to holdings in Michigan).</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_a47c5667e43174a2095e1d9f238837cf">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Organized into two series: I. Correspondence, 1880-1950. II. Financial and Real Estate Records, 1837-1902.</p>  
      </arrangement>
